ed for its economic benefits, but in this volume tourism receives a unique systematic scrutiny as a medium for cultural exchange. Modern developments in technology and industry, together with masterful advertising, have created temporarily leisured people with the desire and the means to travel. They often in turn effect profound cultural change in the places they visit, and the contributors to this work all attend to the impact these "guests" have on their "hosts."In contrast to the dramatic economic transformations, the social repercussions of tourism are subtle and often recognized only by the indigenous peoples themselves and by the anthropologists who have studied them before and after the introduction of tourism. The case studies in Hosts and Guests examine the five types of tourism—historical, cultural, ethnic, environmental, and recreational—and their impact on diverse societies over a broad geographical range  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aTourism. 4aAnthropology. 4aBusiness. 4aEconomics. 4aFolklore. 4aLinguistics. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aSmith, Valene L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Social Sciencesz978311041361808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn eBook Package Archive 1898-1999 (pre Pub)z978311044252640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220801640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812208016423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812208016.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041361-8  Penn Press eBook Package Social Sciences  a978-3-11-044252-6  Penn eBook Package Archive 